 actual facts instead of just a "hunch."
2. Excel is easy to use for small tasks, but it starts to struggle or even crash when you give it too much information. Python 
handles this by using code to talk to the computer directly, so it doesn't get slowed down by trying to show thousands of rows on 
a screen. With Python, you can write a set of instructions once, and the computer will follow those steps perfectly every time. 
This means you don't have to spend hours clicking the same buttons or filtering the same columns every single day.
3. If I had to handle 10,000 transactions every day, I would use a Python script to do the repetitive work for me. The script
