 sense. Then, it would group the transactions together to tell me the total sales and which items were the most popular. Instead
   of me spending my whole morning sorting through a giant list, the script would give me the final answer in a few seconds.
4. Python is great for the "messy" parts of Business Intelligence. Its main job is often data cleaning, which just means fixing 
typos, removing duplicates, and filling in missing information so the reports are accurate. It is also very useful for moving
 data from different places—like a website and a spreadsheet—and putting them into one clean list. Besides that, it can be used
   to make clear charts or even to predict how many items a store might sell next week based on what happened in the past.
